A debounce function limits the rate at which a function can fire by delaying its execution until a specified time has elapsed since the last invocation, which is useful for optimizing event handlers like search inputs or window resizing.

```javascript
// Debounce function
function debounce(func, delay) {
  let timeoutId;
  return function(...args) {
    clearTimeout(timeoutId);
    timeoutId = setTimeout(() => func.apply(this, args), delay);
  };
}

// Example usage: Debouncing a search function
const searchFunction = debounce((query) => {
  console.log(`Searching for: ${query}`);
}, 300);

// Simulate usage (e.g., on input event)
searchFunction('hello'); // Won't log immediately
setTimeout(() => searchFunction('world'), 100); // Still delayed
setTimeout(() => searchFunction('final'), 400); // Logs after 300ms from last call
```
